---
export const prerender = true;
export const yilMeta = {
  date: '2026-05-07',
  headline: 'More Than It Seemed',
  summary:
    "A silly Google Slides trick, a framework breaking from its roots, and a school that made me genuinely wish I was five years old again. Today's theme: the second layer is usually the interesting one.",
};

import BaseHead from '@/components/BaseHead.astro';
import Header from '@/components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '@/components/Footer.astro';
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <BaseHead
      title="YIL 2026-05-07 — More Than It Seemed | Dan Denney"
      description="A silly Google Slides trick, a framework breaking from its roots, and a school that made me genuinely wish I was five years old again. Today's theme: the second layer is usually the interesting one."
    />
  </head>
  <body class="bg-white">
    <main class="relative z-10 bg-stone-50 shadow-xs">
      <Header />

      <!-- Hero: full-width-statement — left-aligned editorial, serif headline, cream canvas -->
      <section class="bg-stone-50">
        <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-6 py-24">
          <p
            class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.25em] text-stone-400"
            style="font-family: ui-monospace, 'Cascadia Code', Menlo, monospace; font-weight: 400;"
          >
            2026-05-07 — Yesterday I Learned
          </p>
          <h1
            class="mt-6 text-stone-900"
            style="font-family: Georgia, 'Times New Roman', serif; font-size: clamp(2.5rem, 5vw, 4rem); font-weight: 700; line-height: 1.1;"
          >
            More Than It Seemed
          </h1>
          <p
            class="mt-6 max-w-2xl text-lg leading-relaxed text-stone-600"
            style="font-family: Georgia, 'Times New Roman', serif; font-weight: 400;"
          >
            A silly Google Slides trick, a framework breaking from its roots, and a school that made
            me genuinely wish I was five years old again. Today's theme: the second layer is usually
            the interesting one.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Google Slides: steps layout, accent-1 (amber) -->
      <section class="bg-stone-50">
        <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-6 py-20">
          <!-- pill-h2-bar -->
          <div
            class="inline-flex items-center rounded-full border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-500/10 px-3 py-1"
          >
            <span
              class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.15em] text-amber-600"
              style="font-family: ui-monospace, 'Cascadia Code', Menlo, monospace; font-weight: 600;"
              >Tooling</span
            >
          </div>
          <h2
            class="mt-3 text-stone-900"
            style="font-family: Georgia, 'Times New Roman', serif; font-size: clamp(1.75rem, 3vw, 2.5rem); font-weight: 700; line-height: 1.1;"
          >
            Google Slides Might Actually Vectorize Your Images
          </h2>
          <div class="mt-3 h-0.5 w-12 bg-amber-600"></div>

          <p
            class="mt-8 max-w-2xl text-base leading-relaxed text-stone-600"
            style="font-family: Georgia, 'Times New Roman', serif; font-weight: 400;"
          >
            A newsletter said you can convert Nano Banana AI images to SVG using Google Slides, and
            I had the obvious reaction. But the process is real, the output is reportedly good for
            soft gradients, and the open question — whether it's genuine vectorization or
            raster-in-SVG wrapper — is worth testing. Either way, a productivity tool nobody
            expected to be doing this is apparently doing it.
          </p>

          <div class="mt-10 grid gap-6 sm:grid-cols-2">
            <!-- Step 1 -->
            <div class="rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-500/10 p-6">
              <p
                class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.15em] text-amber-600"
                style="font-family: ui-monospace, 'Cascadia Code', Menlo, monospace; font-weight: 700;"
              >
                Step 01
              </p>
              <h3
                class="mt-2 text-base text-stone-900"
                style="font-family: Georgia, 'Times New Roman', serif; font-weight: 700; line-height: 1.2;"
              >
                Set Up the Workspace
              </h3>
              <p
                class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-stone-600"
                style="font-family: Georgia, 'Times New Roman', serif; font-weight: 400;"
              >
                Download the image locally and check its exact pixel dimensions (e.g. 1792 ×
                2400). In Google Slides, go to File → Page setup → Custom, switch to Pixels, and
                enter those dimensions. Delete the default text boxes. Matching the dimensions
                prevents distortion in the conversion.
              </p>
            </div>

            <!-- Step 2 -->
            <div class="rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-500/10 p-6">
              <p
                class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.15em] text-amber-600"
                style="font-family: ui-monospace, 'Cascadia Code', Menlo, monospace; font-weight: 700;"
              >
                Step 02
              </p>
              <h3
                class="mt-2 text-base text-stone-900"
                style="font-family: Georgia, 'Times New Roman', serif; font-weight: 700; line-height: 1.2;"
              >
                Set the Image as Background
              </h3>
              <p
                class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-stone-600"
                style="font-family: Georgia, 'Times New Roman', serif; font-weight: 400;"
              >
                Insert → Image → Upload from computer. Once placed, right-click and choose "Set
                image as background." This is the key move — it makes Google's internal renderer
                treat the image as the primary slide layer, which appears to trigger the
                vectorization path on export.
              </p>
            </div>

            <!-- Step 3 -->
            <div class="rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-500/10 p-6">
              <p
                class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.15em] text-amber-600"
                style="font-family: ui-monospace, 'Cascadia Code', Menlo, monospace; font-weight: 700;"
              >
                Step 03
              </p>
              <h3
                class="mt-2 text-base text-stone-900"
                style="font-family: Georgia, 'Times New Roman', serif; font-weight: 700; line-height: 1.2;"
              >
                Export as SVG
              </h3>
              <p
                class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-stone-600"
                style="font-family: Georgia, 'Times New Roman', serif; font-weight: 400;"
              >
                File → Download → Scalable Vector Graphics (.svg, current slide). Google runs an
                internal vectorization process that's reportedly good at soft gradients. Open the
                result in a browser or vector editor — worth checking whether it contains actual
                paths or embedded raster data.
              </p>
            </div>

            <!-- Step 4 -->
            <div class="rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-500/10 p-6">
              <p
                class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.15em] text-amber-600"
                style="font-family: ui-monospace, 'Cascadia Code', Menlo, monospace; font-weight: 700;"
              >
                Step 04
              </p>
              <h3
                class="mt-2 text-base text-stone-900"
                style="font-family: Georgia, 'Times New Roman', serif; font-weight: 700; line-height: 1.2;"
              >
                Fix the Aspect Ratio
              </h3>
              <p
                class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-stone-600"
                style="font-family: Georgia, 'Times New Roman', serif; font-weight: 400;"
              >
                The exported SVG may default to a 1:1 square container regardless of page setup,
                leaving white-space gaps. Open in Figma or Inkscape and crop the canvas to the
                artwork edges. Even with this cleanup step, the gradient quality may beat most
                dedicated raster-to-vector tools.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Remix: prose layout, accent-2 (indigo) -->
      <section class="bg-stone-50">
        <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-6 py-20">
          <!-- pill-h2-bar -->
          <div
            class="inline-flex items-center rounded-full border border-indigo-500/30 bg-indigo-500/10 px-3 py-1"
          >
            <span
              class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.15em] text-indigo-600"
              style="font-family: ui-monospace, 'Cascadia Code', Menlo, monospace; font-weight: 600;"
              >Frameworks</span
            >
          </div>
          <h2
            class="mt-3 text-stone-900"
            style="font-family: Georgia, 'Times New Roman', serif; font-size: clamp(1.75rem, 3vw, 2.5rem); font-weight: 700; line-height: 1.1;"
          >
            Remix 3 Is Trying to Be More Than a React Framework
          </h2>
          <div class="mt-3 h-0.5 w-12 bg-indigo-600"></div>

          <div class="mt-10 max-w-2xl space-y-5">
            <p
              class="text-base leading-relaxed text-stone-600"
              style="font-family: Georgia, 'Times New Roman', serif; font-weight: 400;"
            >
              The Remix 3 beta preview dropped React as a hard dependency. That's the headline, but
              the more interesting thing is what it signals: a framework that was essentially "React
              Router plus conventions" is willing to rethink that identity at version 3.
            </p>
            <p
              class="text-base leading-relaxed text-stone-600"
              style="font-family: Georgia, 'Times New Roman', serif; font-weight: 400;"
            >
              Mature JS frameworks decoupling from their original rendering substrate is worth
              tracking. The surprising thing isn't "no React" — it's that frameworks are
              increasingly defining themselves by what they do for the web, not by which library
              they wrap. Remix is trying to be a web framework that happens to support React, not
              the other way around.
            </p>
            <p>
              <a
                href="https://remix.run/blog/remix-3-beta-preview"
                target="_blank"
                rel="noopener noreferrer"
                class="text-sm text-indigo-600 underline decoration-indigo-300 transition-colors hover:decoration-indigo-600"
                style="font-family: ui-monospace, 'Cascadia Code', Menlo, monospace;"
                >remix.run/blog/remix-3-beta-preview →</a
              >
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Quote: standalone-dark-band -->
      <section style="background: #1E293B;">
        <div class="relative mx-auto max-w-4xl overflow-hidden px-6 py-20">
          <div
            aria-hidden="true"
            class="pointer-events-none absolute -left-4 -top-10 select-none text-[16rem] leading-none text-white/5"
            style="font-family: Georgia, 'Times New Roman', serif; font-weight: 700;"
          >
            "
          </div>
          <blockquote class="relative max-w-3xl">
            <p
              class="text-2xl text-white sm:text-3xl"
              style="font-family: Georgia, 'Times New Roman', serif; font-weight: 400; line-height: 1.4;"
            >
              With a personal tutor, scores are a function of effort.
            </p>
            <footer class="mt-6 flex items-center gap-3">
              <div class="h-px w-8 bg-emerald-500/60"></div>
              <cite
                class="not-italic text-sm text-slate-400"
                style="font-family: ui-monospace, 'Cascadia Code', Menlo, monospace; font-weight: 400;"
              >
                <a
                  href="https://luma.com/nhsz659m"
                  class="transition-colors hover:text-white"
                  target="_blank"
                  rel="noopener noreferrer">Joe Liemandt, Alpha School</a
                >
              </cite>
            </footer>
          </blockquote>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Alpha School: cards layout, accent-3 (emerald) -->
      <section class="bg-stone-50">
        <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-6 py-20">
          <!-- pill-h2-bar -->
          <div
            class="inline-flex items-center rounded-full border border-emerald-500/30 bg-emerald-500/10 px-3 py-1"
          >
            <span
              class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.15em] text-emerald-600"
              style="font-family: ui-monospace, 'Cascadia Code', Menlo, monospace; font-weight: 600;"
              >Education</span
            >
          </div>
          <h2
            class="mt-3 text-stone-900"
            style="font-family: Georgia, 'Times New Roman', serif; font-size: clamp(1.75rem, 3vw, 2.5rem); font-weight: 700; line-height: 1.1;"
          >
            90% of Learning Is Wanting To
          </h2>
          <div class="mt-3 h-0.5 w-12 bg-emerald-600"></div>

          <p
            class="mt-8 max-w-2xl text-base leading-relaxed text-stone-600"
            style="font-family: Georgia, 'Times New Roman', serif; font-weight: 400;"
          >
            I went to a meetup and came away unusually inspired. Joe Liemandt — who was writing
            about AI in the 1980s and building with it in the 90s — walked through how Alpha School
            uses AI-driven personal tutors in 2-hour Pomodoro sprints. The AI handles instruction.
            But his thesis is that 90% of learning's impact comes from motivation, not instruction.
            The guides at Alpha focus almost entirely on that.
          </p>

          <div class="mt-10 grid gap-6 sm:grid-cols-2">
            <!-- Card 1: Post-game press conference -->
            <div
              class="rounded-xl border border-emerald-500/30 bg-white p-6 transition-shadow hover:shadow-md"
            >
              <p
                class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.15em] text-emerald-600"
                style="font-family: ui-monospace, 'Cascadia Code', Menlo, monospace; font-weight: 600;"
              >
                Authenticity over abstraction
              </p>
              <h3
                class="mt-2 text-base text-stone-900"
                style="font-family: Georgia, 'Times New Roman', serif; font-weight: 700; line-height: 1.2;"
              >
                The Post-Game Press Conference
              </h3>
              <p
                class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-stone-600"
                style="font-family: Georgia, 'Times New Roman', serif; font-weight: 400;"
              >
                They don't teach "public speaking." They train kids for the post-game press
                conference — with real reporters. The skill is identical; the context is one a kid
                actually wants to be competent in. Stakes are real. Effort follows.
              </p>
            </div>

            <!-- Card 2: Contract negotiation -->
            <div
              class="rounded-xl border border-emerald-500/30 bg-white p-6 transition-shadow hover:shadow-md"
            >
              <p
                class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.15em] text-emerald-600"
                style="font-family: ui-monospace, 'Cascadia Code', Menlo, monospace; font-weight: 600;"
              >
                Authenticity over abstraction
              </p>
              <h3
                class="mt-2 text-base text-stone-900"
                style="font-family: Georgia, 'Times New Roman', serif; font-weight: 700; line-height: 1.2;"
              >
                Contract Negotiation as Math Class
              </h3>
              <p
                class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-stone-600"
                style="font-family: Georgia, 'Times New Roman', serif; font-weight: 400;"
              >
                Math isn't taught as abstract exercises. It's taught through negotiating contracts.
                The math is identical; the reason to care is completely different. Motivation
                precedes learning — not the other way around.
              </p>
            </div>

            <!-- Card 3: Top 1% -->
            <div
              class="rounded-xl border border-emerald-500/30 bg-white p-6 transition-shadow hover:shadow-md"
            >
              <p
                class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.15em] text-emerald-600"
                style="font-family: ui-monospace, 'Cascadia Code', Menlo, monospace; font-weight: 600;"
              >
                The proof
              </p>
              <h3
                class="mt-2 text-base text-stone-900"
                style="font-family: Georgia, 'Times New Roman', serif; font-weight: 700; line-height: 1.2;"
              >
                Top 1% on Standardized Tests
              </h3>
              <p
                class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-stone-600"
                style="font-family: Georgia, 'Times New Roman', serif; font-weight: 400;"
              >
                Alpha students score in the top 1% on standardized tests. Two hours of AI-based
                personal tutoring per day in focused sprints, with the rest of the time on
                motivation, project, and engagement work. The scores suggest the model is working.
              </p>
            </div>

            <!-- Card 4: Personal reflection -->
            <div
              class="rounded-xl border border-emerald-500/30 bg-white p-6 transition-shadow hover:shadow-md"
            >
              <p
                class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.15em] text-emerald-600"
                style="font-family: ui-monospace, 'Cascadia Code', Menlo, monospace; font-weight: 600;"
              >
                Personal take
              </p>
              <h3
                class="mt-2 text-base text-stone-900"
                style="font-family: Georgia, 'Times New Roman', serif; font-weight: 700; line-height: 1.2;"
              >
                I Rarely Wish I Were Younger
              </h3>
              <p
                class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-stone-600"
                style="font-family: Georgia, 'Times New Roman', serif; font-weight: 400;"
              >
                I left that meetup unusually inspired. I rarely wish to be younger — but I agree
                with Joe that it's a genuinely great time to be a 5-year-old. The trajectories
                available to kids starting in an environment like Alpha feel very different from
                what came before.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- References -->
      <section class="bg-stone-50">
        <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-6 py-16">
          <p
            class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.25em] text-stone-400"
            style="font-family: ui-monospace, 'Cascadia Code', Menlo, monospace; font-weight: 400;"
          >
            References
          </p>
          <div class="mt-6 space-y-4">
            <!-- Tooling — no URL available -->
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
              <span
                class="inline-flex items-center rounded-full border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-500/10 px-2.5 py-0.5 text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.1em] text-amber-600"
                style="font-family: ui-monospace, 'Cascadia Code', Menlo, monospace; font-weight: 600;"
                >tooling</span
              >
              <span
                class="text-sm text-stone-500"
                style="font-family: Georgia, 'Times New Roman', serif; font-weight: 400;"
                >Simplifying AI Newsletter — Nano Banana SVG workflow</span
              >
            </div>
            <!-- Frameworks -->
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
              <span
                class="inline-flex items-center rounded-full border border-indigo-500/30 bg-indigo-500/10 px-2.5 py-0.5 text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.1em] text-indigo-600"
                style="font-family: ui-monospace, 'Cascadia Code', Menlo, monospace; font-weight: 600;"
                >frameworks</span
              >
              <a
                href="https://remix.run/blog/remix-3-beta-preview"
                target="_blank"
                rel="noopener noreferrer"
                class="text-sm text-stone-900 underline decoration-stone-200 transition-colors hover:decoration-indigo-500"
                style="font-family: Georgia, 'Times New Roman', serif; font-weight: 400;"
                >Remix 3 Beta Preview</a
              >
            </div>
            <!-- Education -->
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
              <span
                class="inline-flex items-center rounded-full border border-emerald-500/30 bg-emerald-500/10 px-2.5 py-0.5 text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.1em] text-emerald-600"
                style="font-family: ui-monospace, 'Cascadia Code', Menlo, monospace; font-weight: 600;"
                >education</span
              >
              <a
                href="https://luma.com/nhsz659m"
                target="_blank"
                rel="noopener noreferrer"
                class="text-sm text-stone-900 underline decoration-stone-200 transition-colors hover:decoration-emerald-500"
                style="font-family: Georgia, 'Times New Roman', serif; font-weight: 400;"
                >Meetup: Joe Liemandt on AI and Education</a
              >
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Design Notes -->
      <section class="border-t border-stone-200 bg-stone-100">
        <div class="mx-auto max-w-5xl px-6 py-12">
          <p
            class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.25em] text-stone-400"
            style="font-family: ui-monospace, 'Cascadia Code', Menlo, monospace; font-weight: 400;"
          >
            Design Notes
          </p>
          <p
            class="mt-2 text-sm font-medium text-stone-600"
            style="font-family: Georgia, 'Times New Roman', serif;"
          >
            YIL 2026-05-07 — More Than It Seemed
          </p>
          <p
            class="mt-1 text-sm text-stone-400"
            style="font-family: Georgia, 'Times New Roman', serif; font-weight: 400;"
          >
            Three discoveries — a silly tool trick, a framework outgrowing its origins, and a school
            that made me want to be five again — all turned out to have more going on underneath the
            surface.
          </p>
          <div class="mt-4 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-1.5">
              <span class="h-3 w-3 rounded-full" style="background: #D97706"></span>
              <span
                class="text-[10px] text-stone-400"
                style="font-family: ui-monospace, 'Cascadia Code', Menlo, monospace;"
                >accent-1 / text-amber-600 — tooling / google slides</span
              >
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-center gap-1.5">
              <span class="h-3 w-3 rounded-full" style="background: #4F46E5"></span>
              <span
                class="text-[10px] text-stone-400"
                style="font-family: ui-monospace, 'Cascadia Code', Menlo, monospace;"
                >accent-2 / text-indigo-600 — frameworks / remix</span
              >
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-center gap-1.5">
              <span class="h-3 w-3 rounded-full" style="background: #059669"></span>
              <span
                class="text-[10px] text-stone-400"
                style="font-family: ui-monospace, 'Cascadia Code', Menlo, monospace;"
                >accent-3 / text-emerald-600 — education / alpha school</span
              >
            </div>
          </div>
          <p
            class="mt-6 max-w-2xl text-sm leading-relaxed text-stone-400"
            style="font-family: Georgia, 'Times New Roman', serif; font-weight: 400;"
          >
            This day's visual personality is warm and editorial — a personal learning journal entry,
            not a tech blog post. The cream/stone surface and serif headline communicate "someone
            thinking out loud" rather than "documentation." Three distinct accent colors (amber,
            indigo, emerald) give each section its own identity without fighting each other, and the
            dark-slate quote band provides the one moment of genuine contrast, anchoring Joe
            Liemandt's line as the emotional center of the page. The layout is deliberately
            unhurried: full-width prose opening, generous whitespace, and a steps layout for the
            only genuinely step-based content (the Google Slides workflow). The through-line —
            things with unexpected depth underneath — should feel implicit in the structure, not
            stated again in every section.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>
    </main>
    <Footer />
  </body>
</html>
